                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3546.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Chihuahua</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Chihuahua</hi>
                        </placeName>. <lb/> ([<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1912-04-10">undated</date>;] Received April 10, 1912—2.30
                        p.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Parral taken 4th instant without struggle by rebels, Villa retreating. Violence
                    prevailed; none was respected. Americans suffered less than other foreigners.
                    Salazar commanded rebels. I suggest that occurrences at Parral, which will
                    circulate among Americans here, offer reason for quiet suggestions from this
                    office to Americans to leave as fast as may be consistent with good order.
                    Request instructions as to discreet steps this direction.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
